#. Tag: title
#: deployment_pxe.xml:12
#, no-c-format
msgid "Preparing network boot environment"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:15
#, no-c-format
msgid "This chapter describes how to configure a DHCP and a TFTP server that provide the required infrastructure for booting with PXE."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:26
#, no-c-format
msgid "&productnamereg; can be installed via a Preboot Execution Environment (PXE). The client hardware needs to support booting via PXE. The network needs to provide a DHCP server and a TFTP server providing the required data to the clients. This chapter guides you through setting up the required servers."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:33
#, no-c-format
msgid "PXE only boots a kernel and initrd. This can be used to boot into an installation environment or into live systems. To set up the installation sources, see <xref linkend=\"cha-deployment-instserver\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:39
#, no-c-format
msgid "This section covers the configuration tasks needed in complex boot scenarios. It contains ready-to-apply configuration examples for DHCP, PXE boot, TFTP, and Wake on LAN."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:44
#, no-c-format
msgid "The examples assume that the DHCP, TFTP and NFS server reside on the same machine with the IP <literal>192.168.1.1</literal> . All services can reside on different machines without any problems. Make sure to change the IP addresses as required."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: deployment_pxe.xml:52
#, no-c-format
msgid "Setting up a DHCP server"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:53
#, no-c-format
msgid "A DHCP server provides both dynamic ( <xref linkend=\"sec-deployment-dhcp-dynamic\"/> ) and static IP address assignments ( <xref linkend=\"sec-deployment-dhcp-static\"/> ) to your network clients. It advertises servers, routes, and domains. For TFTP servers, DHCP also provides the kernel and initrd files. Which files are loaded depends on the architecture of the target machine, and whether legacy BIOS or UEFI boot is used. The clients transmit their architecture type in their DHCP requests. Based on this information, the DHCP server decides which files the client must download for booting."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: deployment_pxe.xml:65
#, no-c-format
msgid "PXE and &ay; installation failure"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:66
#, no-c-format
msgid "Starting with &sle; 15.0, there are special conditions that cause PXE boot and &ay; installations to fail. See <xref linkend=\"sec-deployment-dhcp-rfc4361\"/> for more information and the solution."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: deployment_pxe.xml:75
#, no-c-format
msgid "Dynamic address assignment"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:76
#, no-c-format
msgid "The following example shows how to set up a DHCP server that dynamically assigns IP addresses to clients, and advertises servers, routers, domains, and boot files."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:83
#, no-c-format
msgid "Log in as &rootuser; to the machine hosting the DHCP server."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:88
#, no-c-format
msgid "Enable the DHCP server by executing <command>systemctl enable dhcpd</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:94
#, no-c-format
msgid "Append the following lines to a subnet configuration of your DHCP server's configuration file located under <filename>/etc/dhcpd.conf</filename> :"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:99
#, no-c-format
msgid "# The following lines are optional\n"
      "option domain-name \"my.lab\";\n"
      "option domain-name-servers 192.168.1.1;\n"
      "option routers 192.168.1.1;\n"
      "option ntp-servers 192.168.1.1;\n"
      "ddns-update-style none;\n"
      "default-lease-time 3600;\n"
      "\n"
      "# The following lines are required\n"
      "option arch code 93 = unsigned integer 16; # RFC4578\n"
      "subnet 192.168.1.0 netmask 255.255.255.0 {\n"
      " next-server 192.168.1.1;\n"
      " range 192.168.1.100 192.168.1.199;\n"
      " default-lease-time 3600;\n"
      " max-lease-time 3600;\n"
      " if option arch = 00:07 or option arch = 00:09 {\n"
      "   filename \"/EFI/x86/grub.efi\";\n"
      " }\n"
      " else if option arch = 00:0b {\n"
      "   filename \"/EFI/aarch64/bootaa64.efi\";\n"
      " }\n"
      " else  {\n"
      "   filename \"/BIOS/x86/pxelinux.0\";\n"
      " }\n"
      "}"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:124
#, no-c-format
msgid "This configuration example uses the subnet <literal>192.168.1.0/24</literal> with the DHCP, DNS and gateway on the server with the IP <literal>192.168.1.1</literal> . Make sure that all IP addresses are changed according to your network layout. For more information about the options available in <filename>dhcpd.conf</filename> , refer to the <systemitem>dhcpd.conf</systemitem> manual page."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:135
#, no-c-format
msgid "Restart the DHCP server by executing <command>systemctl restart dhcpd</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: deployment_pxe.xml:144
#, no-c-format
msgid "Assigning static IP addresses"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:145
#, no-c-format
msgid "A DHCP server may also assign static IP addresses and host names to network clients. One use case is assigning static addresses to servers. Another use case is restricting which clients may join the network to those with assigned static IP addresses, and providing no dynamic address pools."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:152
#, no-c-format
msgid "Modify the above DHCP configuration according to the following example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:155
#, no-c-format
msgid "group {\n"
      " host test {\n"
      "   hardware ethernet <replaceable>MAC_ADDRESS</replaceable>;\n"
      "   fixed-address <replaceable>IP_ADDRESS</replaceable>;\n"
      "   }\n"
      "}\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:162
#, no-c-format
msgid "The host statement assigns a host name to the installation target. To bind the host name and IP address to a specific host, you must specify the client's hardware (MAC) address. Replace all the variables used in this example with the actual values that match your environment, then save your changes and restart the DHCP server."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: deployment_pxe.xml:172
#, no-c-format
msgid "PXE and &ay; installation failures"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:173
#, no-c-format
msgid "Starting with &sle; 15.0 and ISC DHCP 4.3.x, there are special circumstances that cause PXE boot and &ay; installations to fail. If your DHCP server does not have a pool of available dynamic IP addresses, but allows only pre-defined static addresses per client, and the clients send RFC 4361 client identifiers, then PXE/&ay; installations will not work. (Allowing only addresses assigned to specific network clients, and providing no dynamic address pools, prevents random machines from joining the network.)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:182
#, no-c-format
msgid "When a new system starts in PXE, it sends a request to the DHCP server and identifies itself using a client identifier constructed from the hardware type plus the MAC address of the network interface. This is an RFC 2132 <literal>client-id</literal> . The DHCP server then offers the assigned IP address. Next, the installation kernel is loaded, and sends another DHCP request, but this <literal>client-id</literal> is different, and is sent in RFC 4361 format. The DHCP server will not recognize this as the same client, and will look for a free dynamic IP address, which is not available, and the installation stops."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:191
#, no-c-format
msgid "The solution is to configure clients to send RFC 2132 client IDs. To send an RFC 2132 <literal>client-id</literal> during the installation, use <literal>linuxrc</literal> to pass the following <literal>ifcfg</literal> command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:197
#, no-c-format
msgid "ifcfg=eth0=dhcp,DHCLIENT_CLIENT_ID=<replaceable>01:03:52:54:00:02:c2:67</replaceable>,\n"
      "DHCLIENT6_CLIENT_ID=<replaceable>00:03:52:54:00:02:c2:67</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:199
#, no-c-format
msgid "The traditionally-used RFC 2132 DHCPv4 <literal>client-id</literal> on Ethernet is constructed from the hardware type ( <literal>01</literal> for Ethernet) and followed by the hardware address (the MAC address), for example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:205
#, no-c-format
msgid "01:52:54:00:02:c2:67"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:206
#, no-c-format
msgid "The RFC 4361 DHCPv4 <literal>client-id</literal> attempts to correct the problem of identifying a machine that has more than one network interface. The new DHCPv4 <literal>client-id</literal> has the same format as the DHCPv6 <literal>client-id</literal> . It starts with the <literal>0xff</literal> prefix, instead of the hardware type, followed by the DHCPv6 IAID (the interface-address association ID that describes the interface on the machine), followed by the DHCPv6 Unique Identifier (DUID), which uniquely identifies the machine."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:216
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using the above hardware type-based and hardware address-based DUID, the new RFC 4361 DHCPv4 <literal>client-id</literal> would be:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:222
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using the last bytes of the MAC address as the IAID: <literal>ff:00:02:c2:67:00:01:xx:xx:xx:xx:52:54:00:02:c2:67</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:228
#, no-c-format
msgid "When the IAID is a simple incremented number: <literal>ff:00:00:00:01:00:01:xx:xx:xx:xx:52:54:00:02:c2:67</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:234
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <replaceable>xx:xx:xx:xx</replaceable> field in the DUID-Link-Layer Timestamp (DUID-LLT) is a creation time stamp. A DUID-Link-Layer (DUID-LL) ( <literal>00:03:00:01:$MAC</literal> ) does not have a time stamp."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:239
#, no-c-format
msgid "For more information on using <literal>linuxrc</literal> , see the &ayguide;. Also see <literal>man 4 initrd</literal> , and the documentation for the options <literal>dhcp4 \"create-cid\"</literal> , <literal>dhcp6 \"default-duid\"</literal> in <literal>man 5 wicked-config</literal> , <literal>wicked duid --help</literal> , and <literal>wicked iaid --help</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: deployment_pxe.xml:251
#, no-c-format
msgid "Setting up a TFTP server"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:252
#, no-c-format
msgid "The following procedure describes how to prepare the server so that the client machines with UEFI and BIOS can boot remotely using files exported by TFTP."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: deployment_pxe.xml:258
#, no-c-format
msgid "Installing a TFTP server"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:259
#, no-c-format
msgid "To install a TFTP server, use the following procedure:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:265
#, no-c-format
msgid "Install the <systemitem>tftp</systemitem> package."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:268
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;<command>zypper in tftp</command>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:271
#, no-c-format
msgid "Review the <systemitem class=\"daemon\">tftpd</systemitem> configuration in <filename>/etc/sysconfig/tftp</filename> and add or change options as required. Refer to <command>man 8 tftpd</command> for more details. The TFTP daemon works without changing the configuration. The default root directory for the files is <filename>/srv/tftpboot</filename> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:280
#, no-c-format
msgid "Ensure that <systemitem class=\"daemon\">tftpd</systemitem> is started at boot time, and restart it to read the new configuration."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:284
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;<command>systemctl enable tftp.socket</command>\n"
      "&prompt.sudo;<command>systemctl restart tftp.socket</command>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: deployment_pxe.xml:290
#, no-c-format
msgid "Installing files for boot"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:291
#, no-c-format
msgid "&productname; provides the required files for booting via PXE on BIOS or UEFI machines. The following hardware architectures are supported:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:298
#, no-c-format
msgid "&x86-64;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:303
#, no-c-format
msgid "&aarch64;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:308
#, no-c-format
msgid "&power;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:313
#, no-c-format
msgid "&zseries;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:319
#, no-c-format
msgid "Files required to boot from a specific hardware architecture are included in an RPM package. Install it on the machine running the TFTP server:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:323
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;<command>zypper in tftpboot-installation-SLE-<replaceable>OS_VERSION</replaceable>-<replaceable>ARCHITECTURE</replaceable></command>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:324
#, no-c-format
msgid "Replace <replaceable>OS_VERSION</replaceable> with the version number of your &productname; installation, for example <replaceable>SLE-15-SP2-x86_64</replaceable> , and replace <replaceable>ARCHITECTURE</replaceable> with the architecture of your system, for example <literal>x86_64</literal> . So the resulting text would look like this: <package>tftpboot-installation-SLE-15-SP2-x86_64</package> . Run <command>zypper se tftpboot</command> to search for all available versions and architectures."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:334
#, no-c-format
msgid "The files will be installed in <filename>/srv/tftpboot/SLE-<replaceable>OS_VERSION</replaceable>-<replaceable>ARCHITECTURE</replaceable></filename> . You can also copy the files for other versions and architectures of &productname; to the <filename>/srv/tftpboot</filename> directory."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: deployment_pxe.xml:341
#, no-c-format
msgid "Serving different architectures"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:342
#, no-c-format
msgid "The client and server hardware architecture can vary. For example, you can run an &x86-64; TFTP server and provide a bootable environment for &aarch64; client machines by installing the <package>tftpboot-installation-SLE-15-SP2-aarch64</package> package."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: deployment_pxe.xml:350
#, no-c-format
msgid "Existing <filename>/srv/tftpboot/</filename> directory"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:351
#, no-c-format
msgid "If the directory <filename>/srv/tftpboot/</filename> already exists on your machine, then all files will be installed to <filename>/usr/share/tftpboot-installation/</filename> . This is the case if you are upgrading your PXE server from a previous &slsa; release."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:358
#, no-c-format
msgid "To fix this problem, copy the files manually from <filename>/usr/share/tftpboot-installation/</filename> to <filename>/srv/tftpboot/</filename> . Alternatively, remove <filename>/srv/tftpboot/</filename> and reinstall the <package>tftpboot-installation-SLE-<replaceable>OS_VERSION</replaceable>-<replaceable>ARCHITECTURE</replaceable></package> package."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: deployment_pxe.xml:369
#, no-c-format
msgid "Configuring PXELINUX"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:370
#, no-c-format
msgid "Open the file <filename>/srv/tftpboot/SLE-<replaceable>OS_VERSION</replaceable>-<replaceable>ARCHITECTURE</replaceable>/net/pxelinux.cfg/default</filename> in an editor. Replace the path for the <literal>install</literal> parameter according to your setup as described in <xref linkend=\"cha-deployment-instserver\"/> . Also replace <replaceable>TFTP_SERVER</replaceable> with the IP address of the TFTP server. For an overview of the PXELINUX configuration options, see <xref linkend=\"sec-deployment-prep-boot-pxeopts\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:380
#, no-c-format
msgid "default linux\n"
      "\n"
      "# install\n"
      "label linux\n"
      "  ipappend 2\n"
      "  kernel boot/<replaceable>ARCHITECTURE</replaceable>/loader/linux\n"
      "  append initrd=boot/<replaceable>ARCHITECTURE</replaceable>/loader/initrd instsys=tftp://<replaceable>TFTP_SERVER</replaceable>/SLE-<replaceable>OS_VERSION</replaceable>-<replaceable>ARCHITECTURE</replaceable>/boot/<replaceable>ARCHITECTURE</replaceable>/root install=<replaceable>PROTOCOL</replaceable>://<replaceable>SERVER_IP</replaceable>:/<replaceable>PATH</replaceable>\n"
      "\n"
      "display  message\n"
      "implicit 1\n"
      "prompt  1\n"
      "timeout  50"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:392
#, no-c-format
msgid "For details about the boot parameters that are used in the <literal>append</literal> line, see <xref linkend=\"sec-boot-parameters-list\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:396
#, no-c-format
msgid "If required, edit the <filename>/srv/tftpboot/SLE-<replaceable>OS_VERSION</replaceable>-<replaceable>ARCHITECTURE</replaceable>/net/pxelinux.cfg/message</filename> to display a message in the boot menu."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: deployment_pxe.xml:403
#, no-c-format
msgid "Preparing PXE boot for EFI with GRUB2"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:404
#, no-c-format
msgid "Normally, the GRUB2 configuration files require no modifications. However, the default settings do not include a network resource for the installation system. To perform a full &productname; installation via network, you need to specify the <option>install</option> parameter in the <option>linuxefi</option> instruction of the <filename>/srv/tftpboot/SLE-<replaceable>OS_VERSION</replaceable>-<replaceable>ARCHITECTURE</replaceable>/EFI/BOOT/grub.cfg</filename> file. Refer to <xref linkend=\"sec-boot-parameters-list-install-source\"/> for further information about the <option>install</option> parameter."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: deployment_pxe.xml:419
#, no-c-format
msgid "PXELINUX configuration options"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:421
#, no-c-format
msgid "The options listed here are a subset of all the options available for the PXELINUX configuration file."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: deployment_pxe.xml:428
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>APPEND <replaceable>OPTIONS</replaceable></option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:431
#, no-c-format
msgid "Adds one or more options to the kernel command line. These are added for both automatic and manual boots. The options are added at the very beginning of the kernel command line, usually permitting explicitly entered kernel options to override them."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: deployment_pxe.xml:440
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>APPEND -</option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:443
#, no-c-format
msgid "Appends nothing. <option>APPEND</option> with a single hyphen as argument in a <option>LABEL</option> section can be used to override a global <option>APPEND</option> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: deployment_pxe.xml:451
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>DEFAULT <replaceable>KERNEL_OPTIONS</replaceable>...</option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:454
#, no-c-format
msgid "Sets the default kernel command line. If PXELINUX boots automatically, it acts as if the entries after DEFAULT had been typed in at the boot prompt, except the auto option is automatically added, indicating an automatic boot."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:460
#, no-c-format
msgid "If no configuration file exists or no DEFAULT entry is defined in the configuration file, the default is the kernel name <quote>linux</quote> with no options."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: deployment_pxe.xml:469
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>IFAPPEND <replaceable>FLAG</replaceable></option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:472
#, no-c-format
msgid "Adds a specific option to the kernel command line depending on the <replaceable>FLAG</replaceable> value. The <option>IFAPPEND</option> option is available only on PXELINUX. <replaceable>FLAG</replaceable> expects a value, described in <xref linkend=\"tab-deployment-boot-pxeopts-ifappend\"/> :"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: deployment_pxe.xml:480
#, no-c-format
msgid "Generated and added kernel command line options from <option>IFAPPEND</option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:492
#, no-c-format
msgid "Generated kernel command line / Description"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:501
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>1</option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:506
#, no-c-format
msgid "ip=<replaceable>CLIENT_IP</replaceable>:<replaceable>BOOT_SERVER_IP</replaceable>:<replaceable>GW_IP</replaceable>:<replaceable>NETMASK</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:507
#, no-c-format
msgid "The placeholders are replaced based on the input from the DHCP/BOOTP or PXE boot server."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:511
#, no-c-format
msgid "Note, this option is not a substitute for running a DHCP client in the booted system. Without regular renewals, the lease acquired by the PXE BIOS will expire, making the IP address available for reuse by the DHCP server."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:521
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>2</option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:526
#, no-c-format
msgid "BOOTIF=<replaceable>MAC_ADDRESS_OF_BOOT_INTERFACE</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:527
#, no-c-format
msgid "This option is useful to avoid timeouts when the installation server probes one LAN interface after another until it gets a reply from a DHCP server. This option allows an initrd program to determine from which interface the system has been booted. linuxrc reads this option and uses this network interface."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:538
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>4</option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:543
#, no-c-format
msgid "SYSUUID=<replaceable>SYSTEM_UUID</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:544
#, no-c-format
msgid "Adds UUIDs in lowercase hexadecimals, see <filename>/usr/share/doc/packages/syslinux/pxelinux.txt</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: deployment_pxe.xml:556
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>LABEL <replaceable>LABEL</replaceable> KERNEL <replaceable>IMAGE</replaceable> APPEND <replaceable>OPTIONS</replaceable>...</option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:560
#, no-c-format
msgid "Indicates that if <replaceable>LABEL</replaceable> is entered as the kernel to boot, PXELINUX should instead boot <replaceable>IMAGE</replaceable> and the specified <option>APPEND</option> options should be used. They replace the ones specified in the global section of the file, before the first <option>LABEL</option> command. The default for <replaceable>IMAGE</replaceable> is the same as <replaceable>LABEL</replaceable> and, if no <option>APPEND</option> is given, the default is to use the global entry (if any). Up to 128 <option>LABEL</option> entries are permitted."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:582
#, no-c-format
msgid "PXELINUX uses the following syntax:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:585
#, no-c-format
msgid "label <replaceable>MYLABEL</replaceable>\n"
      "  kernel <replaceable>MYKERNEL</replaceable>\n"
      "  append <replaceable>MYOPTIONS</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:588
#, no-c-format
msgid "Labels are mangled as if they were file names and they must be unique after mangling. For example, the two labels <quote>v2.6.30</quote> and <quote>v2.6.31</quote> would not be distinguishable under PXELINUX because both mangle to the same DOS file name."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:594
#, no-c-format
msgid "The kernel does not need to be a Linux kernel. It can also be a boot sector or a COMBOOT file."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: deployment_pxe.xml:601
#, no-c-format
msgid "<option>LOCALBOOT <replaceable>TYPE</replaceable></option>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:604
