#. Tag: title
#: deployment_pxe.xml:736
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using wake-on-LAN for remote wakeups"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:737
#, no-c-format
msgid "Wake-on-LAN (WOL) is an Ethernet standard for remotely waking up a computer by sending it a wakeup signal over a network. This signal is called the <quote>magic packet</quote> . Install WOL on client machines to enable remote wakeups, and on every machine you want to use for sending the wakeup signal. The magic packet is broadcast over UDP port 9 to the MAC address of the network interface on the client machine."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:745
#, no-c-format
msgid "When computers are shut down they usually are not turned all the way off, but remain in a low power mode. When the network interface supports WOL, it listens for the magic packet wakeup signal when the machine is powered off. You can send the magic packet manually, or schedule wakeups in a cron job on the sending machine."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: deployment_pxe.xml:754
#, no-c-format
msgid "Prerequisites"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:755
#, no-c-format
msgid "WOL works with both wired and wireless Ethernet cards that support it."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:758
#, no-c-format
msgid "You may need to enable WOL in your system BIOS/UEFI."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:761
#, no-c-format
msgid "Check your BIOS/UEFI settings for PXE boot, and make sure it is disabled to prevent accidental re-installations."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:766
#, no-c-format
msgid "Adjust your firewall to allow traffic over UDP port 9."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: deployment_pxe.xml:772
#, no-c-format
msgid "Verifying wired Ethernet support"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:773
#, no-c-format
msgid "Run the following command to see if a wired Ethernet interface supports WOL:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:777
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;ethtool eth0 | grep -i wake-on\n"
      "Supports Wake-on: pumbg\n"
      "Wake-on: g"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:780
#, no-c-format
msgid "The example output shows that eth0 supports WOL, indicated by the <literal>g</literal> flag on the <literal>Supports Wake-on</literal> line. <literal>Wake-on: g</literal> shows that WOL is already enabled, so this interface is ready to receive wakeup signals. If WOL is not enabled, enable it with this command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:787
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;ethtool -s wol g"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: deployment_pxe.xml:791
#, no-c-format
msgid "Verifying wireless interface support"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:792
#, no-c-format
msgid "Wakeup-over-wifi, or WoWLAN, requires a wireless network interface that supports WoWLAN. Test it with the <command>iw</command> command, which is provided by the <package>iw</package> package:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:797
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;zypper in iw"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:798
#, no-c-format
msgid "Find your device name:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:801
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;iw dev\n"
      "phy#0\n"
      "        Interface wlan2\n"
      "                ifindex 3\n"
      "                wdev 0x1\n"
      "                addr 9c:ef:d5:fe:01:7c\n"
      "                ssid accesspoint\n"
      "                type managed\n"
      "                channel 11 (2462 MHz), width: 20 MHz, center1: 2462 MHz\n"
      "                txpower 20.00 dBm"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:811
#, no-c-format
msgid "In this example, the device name to use for querying WoWLAN support is <literal>phy#0</literal> . This example shows that it is not supported:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:815
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;iw phy#0 wowlan show\n"
      "command failed: Operation not supported (-95)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:817
#, no-c-format
msgid "This example shows an interface that supports WoWLAN, but is not enabled:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:820
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;iw phy#0 wowlan show\n"
      "WoWLAN is disabled"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:822
#, no-c-format
msgid "Enable it:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:825
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;iw phy#0 wowlan enable magic-packet\n"
      "WoWLAN is enabled:\n"
      "* wake up on magic packet"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: deployment_pxe.xml:831
#, no-c-format
msgid "Installing and testing WOL"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:832
#, no-c-format
msgid "To use WOL, install the <package>wol</package> package on the client and sending machines:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:836
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;zypper in wol"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:837
#, no-c-format
msgid "Install <package>wol-udev-rules</package> on your client machines. This package installs a udev rule that enables WOL automatically at start-up."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:841
#, no-c-format
msgid "Get the MAC address of the network interface on the client machine:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:844
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;ip addr show eth0|grep ether\n"
      "link/ether 7c:ef:a5:fe:06:7c brd ff:ff:ff:ff:ff:ff"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:846
#, no-c-format
msgid "In the example output, <literal>7c:ef:a5:fe:06:7c</literal> is the MAC address."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:850
#, no-c-format
msgid "Shut down your client machine, and send it a wakeup signal from another computer on the same subnet:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:854
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;wol <replaceable>7c:ef:a5:fe:06:7c</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:855
#, no-c-format
msgid "If your target machine and second device are on the same network but in different subnets, specify the broadcast address for your target machine:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: deployment_pxe.xml:860
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;wol -i <replaceable>192.168.0.63 7c:ef:a5:fe:06:7c</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:861
#, no-c-format
msgid "Because WOL relies on broadcast domains, the sending machine must be on the same network, though it can be in a different network segment."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: deployment_pxe.xml:865
#, no-c-format
msgid "It is possible to send the magic packet from a different network. One way is with port forwarding, if your router supports port forwarding to a broadcast address. A more secure method is to connect to a host inside your network via SSH, and send the magic packet from there."
msgstr ""

